{"terr": "France","region": "","certLow": 4,"certHigh": 4,"payLow": null,"payHigh": null,"sourceQuality": "government_plus_industry","sourceNote": "Provisional TRIP qualification generally given within ~1 month (~4wk) of submission, per MPC Paris and Trimaran (production service/VFX companies working directly with CNC). Payment mechanism confirmed tied to fiscal-year-end Corporate Tax return cycle (cnc.fr, government-direct) \u2014 structurally like the UK, but total wait depends on where in the fiscal year production wraps. Certification stage now real; full payment-stage week-count still not explicitly stated. [CORRECTED 2026-07: the ~1 month certification figure is from MPC Paris/Trimaran (production service companies), not cnc.fr directly \u2014 downgraded from government_plus_industry. The payment-tied-to-fiscal-year MECHANISM is genuinely cnc.fr-sourced, but the specific timing figure is industry-only. Split accordingly, not blended.] [ADDED 2026-07: separately confirmed via cnc.fr directly that TRIP CAN be discounted at a financial institution as collateral for bridge financing ('under certain conditions provided for by law') -- this is a real, government-confirmed BANKABILITY-AS-COLLATERAL mechanism, distinct from payment-timeline bankability. A specific 85-90% bank discount rate was claimed by an external source but is NOT independently confirmed -- treat the discounting mechanism as real, the specific percentage as unverified.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "","aiNarrativeRule": "UPGRADED 2026-07: certification ~1 month (4wk, industry-sourced). Payment mechanism confirmed government-direct via cnc.fr: tied to fiscal-year-end Corporate Tax return, with a real 3-year legal backstop if unused (PwC tax summary) -- a worst-case ceiling, not a typical wait, never present as the expected timeline. REAL BANKABILITY-AS-COLLATERAL MECHANISM, newly confirmed: IFCIC (Institut pour le Financement du Cinema et des Industries Culturelles), a real CNC/State-affiliated credit institution, offers loan guarantees covering 50-70% of a bank's risk when advancing money against TRIP's provisional approval certificate (confirmed via Film France CNC's own site and IFCIC's own site directly). Legal basis confirmed exact: Article 220 quaterdecies of the French General Tax Code (verified directly against Legifrance, France's official legislation database). REJECTED CLAIM: an AI-generated document (which itself disclosed 'AI responses may include mistakes') asserted a specific '6 to 18 months' payment timeline -- this figure could NOT be independently confirmed from any government or trade source and should NOT be cited as fact. Cite as: certification ~4wk (industry estimate); ordinary payment timing still not independently confirmed; but IFCIC-backed bridge financing (50-70% guarantee) provides a real, government-affiliated mechanism to access the value of TRIP well before the fiscal-year-end payment cycle completes, which is arguably the more practically important bankability fact for producers than the raw payment-stage timeline."},
{"terr": "Singapore","region": "Asia","certLow": null,"certHigh": null,"payLow": null,"payHigh": null,"sourceQuality": "unverified","sourceNote": "Confirmed needs a direct IMDA enquiry \u2014 public sources conflict on whether this is a flat rebate or discretionary co-funding at all, let alone payment timing. [VERIFICATION NOTE 2026-07: a shared external document described an '8-12wk post-audit' disbursement process via IMDA's 'Online Grant Management System (OGMS)'. OGMS is a REAL system (confirmed via imda.gov.sg) but IMDA's own site states OGMS 'will no longer be available from 27 Apr 2024' -- the document describes a RETIRED system as current. Whatever replaced OGMS and its actual current disbursement timeline is NOT confirmed. Do not use the shared document's Singapore timeline.]","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "","aiNarrativeRule": "No usable timeline data exists. IMDA's disbursement system (OGMS) was confirmed retired as of April 2024; what replaced it and its actual timeline is unknown. This requires a direct enquiry to IMDA, not further research \u2014 cite as 'Insufficient Data, direct contact required.'"},
{"terr": "California","region": "North America","certLow": null,"certHigh": null,"payLow": 0,"payHigh": 260,"sourceQuality": "government_direct","sourceNote": "MAJOR FINDING (corrected 2026-07): the refundable portion of the Program 4.0 credit is NOT paid as a lump sum \u2014 it is paid out over 5 YEARS (~52-260 weeks), including the year of election, confirmed directly by FTB.ca.gov and corroborated by Wrapbook. This is a defining bankability characteristic, not a research gap: California's generous 35-45% rate comes with genuinely slow, multi-year cash realization, not a quick payout like Germany or Serbia. Certificate issuance itself follows a 5-phase process (application, allocation, production, audit, Phase V certificate) with no single stated week-count, but the REAL headline fact is the 5-year refund spread.","realWorldConfirms": true,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.ftb.ca.gov/file/business/credits/motion-picture-tv-credit.html","aiNarrativeRule": "REFINED 2026-07 after re-verification against the California Film Commission's own guidance document (cdn.film.ca.gov): the 5-year payout is real and government-confirmed, but only applies to the PORTION OF THE CREDIT EXCEEDING the production's actual California tax liability, and only if the production elects refundability (optional, not automatic, and costs 10% -- refundable value is 90% of face). A production with real CA tax liability can realize most of its credit in year one via direct offset. For the refundable excess, payment is NOT a single lump sum after 5 years -- the Commission's own worked example shows a portion (up to 20% of the refundable amount) disbursed annually, netted against that year's tax liability, with real cash movement starting in year one. Cite as: 'California's headline 35-45% rate can convert to cash faster than the '5-year payout' framing suggests if the production has real CA tax liability to offset; for the portion that doesn't offset, expect a multi-year (up to 5-year) gradual disbursement, not an all-at-once refund and not a 5-year wait with nothing in between.' Confirmed via CA Film Commission (cdn.film.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/4-0-Refundability-Summary.pdf), Wrapbook, Entertainment Partners, Variety (June 2026)."},
{"terr": "New Mexico","region": "North America","certLow": 13,"certHigh": 26,"payLow": 0,"payHigh": 0,"sourceQuality": "industry_secondary","sourceNote": "Refundable credit; \"approval process can take several months\" per Bennett Thrasher (entertainment tax advisory firm) \u2014 estimated ~13-26 weeks. Real but imprecise figure, not independently confirmed against the NM Film Office directly.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.btcpa.net/questions/what-are-the-key-differences-between-refundable-and-transferable-film-tax-credits","aiNarrativeRule": "An industry advisory source estimates 13-26 weeks (\"several months\") for the approval process; the payment stage itself has no confirmed figure. Cite the certification estimate as industry-sourced and unconfirmed by the NM Film Office directly."},
{"terr": "Louisiana","region": "North America","certLow": null,"certHigh": null,"payLow": null,"payHigh": null,"sourceQuality": "government_plus_industry","sourceNote": "REAL RISK HISTORY CONFIRMED (2026-07): the buyback provision (state purchases unused credits at 90% face value, 2% fee) was SUSPENDED for a full year in 2015 after the program's front-end/back-end caps created a backlog \u2014 producers 'couldn't receive refunds on credits they had earned' (Louisiana Illuminator, Verite News, The Advocate \u2014 real journalism, not industry blogs). Program required a major legislative overhaul in 2025 (Act 44) amid continued weakness \u2014 'only one production was active in the state as of May 20 [2025]' per Louisiana Entertainment's own reporting. Mechanism confirmed government-direct (louisianaentertainment.gov): CPA audit -> Initial Certification -> cost report -> Final Certification -> claim on LA return OR 90%-value buyback (2% fee). No specific weeks/months processing figure found, but the REAL PATTERN \u2014 caps creating payment backlogs, precedent of a full-year buyback suspension \u2014 is the same risk signature as Romania. Treat as genuine caution, not just 'insufficient data.' [VERIFICATION NOTE 2026-07: a shared external document claimed a statutory '120-day Final Certification' clock and a '90% buyback (88% net)' rate. Direct check of La. Admin. Code tit. 61, SS I-1607 did NOT confirm a clean 120-day final-cert figure (that section covers initial certification and appeal timing). SS I-6769 explicitly states the buyback rebate is 85% of face value, not 90% -- a direct conflict with the external claim, possibly reflecting a 2025 Act 44 change not yet reflected in the section found, but NOT resolved either way. Do not use the external document's specific figures for Louisiana without further confirmation.]","realWorldConfirms": false,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.louisianaentertainment.gov/film/motion-picture-production-program","aiNarrativeRule": "No specific week-count exists from any source. IMPORTANT REAL RISK HISTORY that must always accompany any mention of Louisiana: the state's buyback provision (90% face value payout) was SUSPENDED for a full year in 2015 after program caps created a payment backlog, and the program required a major legislative overhaul in 2025 amid continued weakness. Cite as 'Insufficient Data' on timing, but always include this real backlog-history caveat."},
{"terr": "Morocco","region": "Africa","certLow": 13,"certHigh": 13,"payLow": 0,"payHigh": 26,"sourceQuality": "government_direct","sourceNote": "CONFIRMED via ccm.ma directly (Centre Cin\u00e9matographique Marocain, the government body itself): 3 months (13wk) post-wrap to submit complete accounts, then CCM processes payment within a MAXIMUM of 180 days (26wk) after the complete payment request file is submitted. Total realistic: ~13-39 weeks. Corroborated by multiple independent industry sources (Atlas Film Fixers: '6-12 months' range; Celluloid Pact: 'typically pays out several months after wrap, not immediately') citing the same real-world pattern, not just repeating the government's stated maximum.","realWorldConfirms": true,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.ccm.ma/foreign_production/pe/index.html","aiNarrativeRule": "Real-world confirmed, government-direct via Morocco's CCM: 3 months (13 weeks) post-wrap to submit accounts, then CCM processes payment within a maximum of 180 days (26 weeks) after a complete payment request file. Total realistic range 13-39 weeks. Cite with confidence as government-direct."},
{"terr": "South Korea","region": "Asia","certLow": null,"certHigh": null,"payLow": 9,"payHigh": 9,"sourceQuality": "government_direct","sourceNote": "PARTIAL, government-direct via koreanfilm.or.kr (KOFIC's own official site): settlement/accounts 'Period of Settlement: Within 2 months from completion of production in Korea' (~9 weeks) is the deadline for the PRODUCTION to submit its accounts \u2014 this is not yet the same as confirming how fast KOFIC then pays out after that submission is received. Real and government-sourced as far as it goes, but the actual payment-processing time after settlement submission is not stated.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/coProduction/locIncentive.jsp","aiNarrativeRule": "Only the accounts-submission deadline is confirmed, government-direct via KOFIC: settlement must be submitted within 2 months (9 weeks) of production completion. The actual PAYMENT processing time after that submission has not been found. Cite the submission deadline with confidence; state payment timing as 'Insufficient Data.'"},
{"terr": "Netherlands","region": "Europe","certLow": 8,"certHigh": 10,"payLow": 8,"payHigh": 8,"sourceQuality": "government_plus_industry","sourceNote": "Decision outcome 'usually follows within eight to ten weeks' of application (filmfonds.nl, government-direct). 30% cash-flow advance confirmed available after signing the production agreement. Full financing/remainder tied to completion within 24 months of the implementation agreement -- competitive, points-based (min 75/210), NOT automatic even after the 8-10wk decision.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.filmfonds.nl/en/funding/fund/netherlands-film-production-incentive","aiNarrativeRule": "UPGRADED 2026-07 on re-verification: found via Variety (corroborating filmcommission.nl) a real, specific payment figure that was previously marked unconfirmed. Full timeline now: decision within 8-10 weeks (government-direct), 30% cash-flow advance available after signing, and the REMAINDER is paid within 8 weeks of submitting required documents after project completion (Variety, corroborating the government's own process description). This is a genuine full-range territory, not partial -- Cite as 'Bankable', competitive/points-based (min 75/210) rather than automatic, but with a real, reasonably fast confirmed timeline once approved."},
{"terr": "Belgium","region": "Europe","certLow": 0,"certHigh": 13,"payLow": 0,"payHigh": 0,"sourceQuality": "government_direct","sourceNote": "STRUCTURAL CLARIFICATION (2026-07): Belgium's Tax Shelter is NOT a rebate-style 'government pays producer' mechanism -- it's investor-funded. Confirmed via Screen Flanders (regional government economic fund body): investors are obliged to pay their FULL investment within 3 months (~13wk) of the Tax Shelter framework agreement being signed. The producer receives real cash from PRIVATE INVESTORS on this timeline; the 'government' component is a tax certificate/benefit to the investor, realized separately via the investor's own tax return, not a direct government-to-producer payment. Bankability for Belgium should be assessed as 'how reliably can a production attract Tax Shelter investors', not 'how fast does the government pay' -- a different question than every other territory in this dataset.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.screenflanders.be/en/financing/other-funds-incentives/tax-shelter","aiNarrativeRule": "STRUCTURAL NOTE that must always accompany Belgium: the Tax Shelter is NOT a government-pays-producer rebate \u2014 it is investor-funded. Investors must pay their full investment within 3 months (13 weeks) of the signed framework agreement; the government's role is a tax certificate to the INVESTOR, realized separately via the investor's own tax return. Never describe Belgium's 'payment timeline' as if it works like a standard rebate \u2014 always frame it as 'how reliably can this production attract Tax Shelter investors within roughly 3 months,' a different question than every other territory in this dataset."},
{"terr": "Czech Republic","region": "Europe","certLow": null,"certHigh": null,"payLow": 13,"payHigh": 13,"sourceQuality": "government_plus_industry","sourceNote": "Mechanism confirmed government-direct (filmcommission.cz / Czech Audiovisual Fund): no aid is paid before the producer has spent its own funds, followed by audit. 'Typical turnaround to receive funds is 3 months (~13wk), unless there are reshoots or post-production' per PSN (industry-secondary) -- consistent with the 2026 restructure toward a larger, more stable annual pool (~EUR87M) confirmed in the earlier incentive audit. Apply-for-payment deadline is 3 years from Decision on Filing (a ceiling, not the typical timeline).","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.filmcommission.cz/en/production-incentives/","aiNarrativeRule": "No clean government-published week-count exists for the overall process, though the mechanism itself (spend-then-audit, no advance payment) is government-confirmed. An industry source estimates a typical 3-month (13-week) turnaround absent reshoots. Cite the mechanism as government-confirmed and the 13-week estimate as industry-sourced."},
{"terr": "\u00cele-de-France","region": "Europe","certLow": 4,"certHigh": 4,"payLow": null,"payHigh": null,"sourceQuality": "industry_secondary","sourceNote": "Shares France's national TRIP baseline (~1 month/4wk provisional certification, payment tied to fiscal-year-end Corporate Tax return) since TRIP is a national programme, not regionally devolved -- same sourcing as the France record. The SEPARATE Ile-de-France regional top-up fund (Fonds de soutien Cinema et Audiovisuel -- selective, repayable, ~EUR180-200K cap) has its own unresearched timeline, distinct from this baseline. Confirmed no film-incentive-specific AEAT-equivalent gap here since France (unlike Spain) does have the TRIP finding to inherit.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "","aiNarrativeRule": "Shares France's national TRIP baseline and the same certification/payment caveats (see France). The separate \u00cele-de-France regional top-up fund (selective, repayable, not a rebate) has its own unresearched timeline \u2014 never conflate it with the TRIP baseline timing."},
{"terr": "New Zealand","region": "Oceania","certLow": 13,"certHigh": 13,"payLow": 2,"payHigh": 2,"sourceQuality": "government_direct","sourceNote": "CONFIRMED via nzfilm.co.nz directly (NZFC's own site): 'The Interim and Final application process takes up to three months' (~13wk) for Rebate Panel approval. 'Once approved, payment is generally made within ten business days after an invoice is submitted' (~2wk) -- this is MORE PRECISE and FASTER than a shared external document's claim of '4 weeks', which was in the right order of magnitude but less accurate than this direct NZFC figure. Total realistic: ~15 weeks.","realWorldConfirms": true,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://www.nzfilm.co.nz/incentives-co-productions/nzspg-international","aiNarrativeRule": "Real-world confirmed, government-direct via NZFC's own site: the application/panel process takes up to 3 months (13 weeks), and payment is made within 10 business days (~2 weeks) of invoice submission once approved. Cite with confidence as government-direct \u2014 this is one of the fastest confirmed payment stages in the dataset."},
{"terr": "Illinois","region": "North America","certLow": null,"certHigh": null,"payLow": 4,"payHigh": 13,"sourceQuality": "industry_secondary","sourceNote": "Mechanism confirmed directly via dceo.illinois.gov: Accredited Production Certificate -> CPA verification (Agreed-Upon Procedures report) -> Tax Credit Certificate -> transferable within 1yr. A shared external document claimed '8-12wk certification, 6-12wk payment via a liquid Chicago broker market' -- this specific week-range and the 'liquid broker market' characterization are NOT confirmed by DCEO/IFO's own materials, which describe the process but commit to no timeframe. Treat as still genuinely undetermined despite the plausible-sounding external claim.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "https://dceo.illinois.gov/whyillinois/film/filmtaxcredit/faqs.html","aiNarrativeRule": "UPGRADED 2026-07: found real, multi-source-corroborated broker-market data previously missing. Illinois's transferable credit 'generally clears in 30 to 90 days (4-13wk) at 88 to 95 cents on the dollar' (Shamel Studio), corroborated by Topsheet's '85-90 cents per dollar' figure. This is industry-sourced (not DCEO directly) but multiply-corroborated and specific. Cite as a real, if industry-sourced, cash-speed figure via the broker market -- genuinely faster and more liquid than several other transferable-credit states in this dataset."},
{"terr": "Spain","region": "Europe","certLow": null,"certHigh": null,"payLow": null,"payHigh": null,"sourceQuality": "unverified","sourceNote": "CATEGORIZED (2026-07): confirmed via three separate research passes that no FILM-SPECIFIC payment SLA is published anywhere -- this is a real, defensible finding, not a search failure. STRUCTURAL REASON WHY: Art 36.2 LIS is a tax DEDUCTION claimed through the standard Corporate Tax return (filed ~July following the fiscal year), processed by AEAT as an ordinary corporate tax refund -- NOT a dedicated film rebate mechanism with its own timeline. This means Spain's real timeline is governed by Spain's GENERAL corporate tax refund process, not a film-specific one. UNVERIFIED LEAD worth checking: Spain's General Tax Law (Ley General Tributaria) is understood to include a general statutory refund deadline (commonly cited as 6 months, after which default interest accrues) that would apply to ANY corporate tax refund including this one -- this figure has NOT been independently confirmed this session and should be verified against the LGT directly before use, but if confirmed it would give Spain a real, government-backed figure via a different legal route than the other territories in this dataset.","realWorldConfirms": null,"suspended": false,"sourceUrl": "","aiNarrativeRule": "No film-incentive-specific timeline exists from any source despite two separate research attempts. The mechanism is a standard Corporate Tax deduction (Art 36.2), which means Spain's general tax-refund statutory framework may apply (commonly understood to carry a general 6-month deadline under the Ley General Tributaria) \u2014 this specific figure has NOT been independently verified and should be checked before use. Cite as 'Insufficient Data' with this unverified lead noted, not asserted as fact."},
